a. [`\def\d{\displaystyle}\def\course{Math 228}\newcommand{\f}[1]{\mathfrak #1}\forall y \exists x P(x,y)`] is true. No matter what [`y`] is (i.e., no matter what column we are in) there is some [`x`] for which [`P(x,y)`] is true. In fact, we can always take [`x`] to be [`3\text{.}`]
a. [`\def\d{\displaystyle}\def\course{Math 228}\newcommand{\f}[1]{\mathfrak #1}\exists x \forall y P(x,y)`] is true. In particular [`x=3`] is such a number, so that no matter what [`y`] is, [`P(x,y)`] is true.
a. [`\def\d{\displaystyle}\def\course{Math 228}\newcommand{\f}[1]{\mathfrak #1}\exists y \forall x P(x,y)`] is false. In fact, no matter what [`y`] (column) we look at, there is always some [`x`] (row) which makes [`P(x,y)`] false.
