BEGIN_PGML Let [`\newcommand{\s}[1]{\mathscr #1}\newcommand{\lt}{<}A = \{x \in \N \st 4 \le x \lt 12\}`] and [`\newcommand{\s}[1]{\mathscr #1}B = \{x \in \N \st x \text{ is even}\}\text{.}`] a. Find [`A \cap B\text{.}`]
[_]{$ans1}{10}
a. Find [`\newcommand{\s}[1]{\mathscr #1}A \setminus B\text{.}`]
[_]{$ans2}{10}
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION a. [`A \cap B`] will be the set of natural numbers that are both at least 4 and less than 12, and even. That is, [`\newcommand{\s}[1]{\mathscr #1}\newcommand{\lt}{<}A \cap B = \{x \in \N \st 4\le x \lt 12 \wedge x \text{ is even}\} = \{4, 6, 8, 10\}\text{.}`]
a. [`\newcommand{\s}[1]{\mathscr #1}A \setminus B`] is the set of all elements that are in [`A`] but not [`B\text{.}`] So this is [`\newcommand{\s}[1]{\mathscr #1}\newcommand{\lt}{<}\{x \in \N \st 4 \le x \lt 12 \wedge x \text{ is odd}\} = \{5,7,9,11\}\text{.}`]
Note this is the same set as [`A \cap \overline{B}\text{.}`]
END_PGML_SOLUTION
