############################################################ # Body ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML Let [`P(x)`] be the predicate, "[`3x+1`] is even." a. Is [`P(5)`] true or false? [_]{$true}{5}
a. What, if anything, can you conclude about [`\exists x P(x)`] from the truth value of [`P(5)\text{?}`]
[@KeyboardInstructions(q?[_]{$exists}{5}?)@]**
a. What, if anything, can you conclude about [`\def\d{\displaystyle}\def\course{Math 228}\newcommand{\f}[1]{\mathfrak #1}\forall x P(x)`] from the truth value of [`P(5)\text{?}`]
[@KeyboardInstructions(q?[_]{$forall}{5}?)@]**
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION [`P(5)`] is the statement "[`3\cdot 5 + 1`] is even", which is true. Thus the statement [`\exists x P(x)`] is true (for example, 5 is such an [`x`]). However, we cannot tell anything about [`\def\d{\displaystyle}\def\course{Math 228}\newcommand{\f}[1]{\mathfrak #1}\forall x P(x)`] since we do not know the truth value of [`P(x)`] for _all_ elements of the domain of discourse. In this case, [`\def\d{\displaystyle}\def\course{Math 228}\newcommand{\f}[1]{\mathfrak #1}\forall x P(x)`] happens to be false (since [`P(4)`] is false, for example).
END_PGML_SOLUTION
